{"source_hash": "82eedd6dae79ef0f", "candidate": {"id": "cand-028", "name": "Chen Wei", "raw_cv": "CHEN WEI\nchen.wei@email.com | London, UK\n\nSITE RELIABILITY ENGINEER\n\nPROFESSIONAL SUMMARY\nSRE with 9 years of experience, including 5 years at Google. Expert in large-scale reliability engineering, capacity planning, and production readiness. Strong background in distributed systems and chaos engineering. Former Google L6 SRE.\n\nEXPERIENCE\n\nStaff SRE \u2014 Revolut, London (2022\u2013present)\n- Technical lead for reliability engineering across the core banking infrastructure (500+ microservices)\n- Defined the production readiness framework adopted by all 80 engineering teams\n- Led the post-incident review process reform, reducing repeat incidents by 40%\n- Designed capacity planning model for the EU/UK banking infrastructure\n\nSenior SRE \u2192 SRE L6 \u2014 Google, London (2017\u20132022)\n- SRE for Google Cloud Spanner \u2014 ensured 99.999% availability at global scale\n- Designed the automated runbook system reducing toil 60% for on-call engineers\n- Led the annual DiRT (Disaster Recovery Test) for Spanner\n- Mentored 4 SREs to promotion\n\nSRE \u2014 Criteo, Paris (2015\u20132017)\n- On-call for ad serving infrastructure processing 1M+ bid requests/second\n\nSKILLS\nGo, Python, C++, Kubernetes, GKE, Terraform, Prometheus, Grafana, Borgmon, SLO/SLI/error budget framework, chaos engineering, capacity planning, incident management\n\nEDUCATION\nMSc Computer Science \u2014 \u00c9cole Polytechnique (2013\u20132015)\nBEng Computer Engineering \u2014 Zhejiang University (2009\u20132013)\n\nRIGHT TO WORK\nFrench citizen, UK Settled Status (ILR)", "raw_linkedin": "Staff SRE at Revolut. Previously Google L6 SRE on Spanner for five years. My job is to make sure complex distributed systems keep working even when the world is trying to break them \u2014 planned and unplanned. I care deeply about toil reduction, good post-incident culture, and treating reliability as an engineering problem with measurable outcomes. French citizen with UK ILR, London-based. Open to staff or principal SRE roles or head of SRE positions at companies serious about reliability.", "raw_interview_transcript": "Interviewer: Chen, thanks for coming in. Tell me about the production readiness framework you defined at Revolut.\n\nChen: When I joined Revolut there were 80 engineering teams and no consistent bar for what 'production ready' meant. Some teams had great runbooks and SLOs; others had neither. I spent three months interviewing teams, looking at incidents, and understanding where reliability failures were actually coming from. I then defined a production readiness review \u2014 a structured checklist covering observability, graceful degradation, capacity, runbooks, and load testing \u2014 that every new service has to pass before its first production launch. It's now mandatory and we've seen a measurable reduction in P1 incidents from new service launches.\n\nInterviewer: How do you think about chaos engineering in a banking context?\n\nChen: Banking is interesting because the risk appetite is lower but the need for resilience is higher than most industries. I've run chaos experiments at Revolut but we do it very carefully \u2014 always in staging first, always with a clear hypothesis and stop condition. The value isn't just finding failures; it's building confidence that your recovery mechanisms actually work. Most companies discover their runbooks are wrong only during actual incidents.\n\nInterviewer: What would you look for in your next role?\n\nChen: I've been doing pure IC work for nine years and I'm interested in leading a reliability engineering function \u2014 not people management for its own sake, but building the team and culture around reliability. I'd want a senior IC path alongside that.\n\nInterviewer: Salary?\n\nChen: I'm at \u00a3145,000 at Revolut. I'd need to be in a similar range.", "years_experience": 9.0, "skills": ["Go", 